{"title_page": "Do not go gentle into that good night", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|Poem by Dylan Thomas}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n\"'''Do not go gentle into that good night'''\" is a poem in the form of a [[villanelle#Form|villanelle]], and the most famous work of [[Welsh literature in English|Welsh poet]] [[Dylan Thomas]] (1914\u20131953).<ref name=poets>{{cite web|url=http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poet/dylan-thomas|title=Dylan Thomas|work=Academy of American Poets|quote=He took his family to Italy, and while in Florence, he wrote ''In Country Sleep, And Other Poems'' (Dent, 1952), which includes his most famous poem, \"Do not go gentle into that good night.\"}}</ref> Though first published in the journal ''[[Botteghe Oscure]]'' in 1951,<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferris |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Ferris (Welsh writer) |title=Dylan Thomas, A Biography |year=1989 |publisher=Paragon House |location=New York |page=283 |isbn=1-55778-215-6}}</ref> it was written in 1947 when Thomas was in [[Florence]] with his family. It was published, along with other stories previously written, as part of Thomas' ''In Country Sleep, And Other Poems'' of 1952.<ref name=poets/> The poem was also included in ''Collected Poems, 1934\u20131952'', first published by [[J. M. Dent|Dent]] in 1952.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biblio.com/collected-poems-1934-1952-by-thomas-dylan/work/13131|title=Collected Poems 1934-1952 by Thomas, Dylan|website=www.biblio.com}}</ref> \n\nIt has been suggested that the poem was written for Thomas' dying father, although he did not die until just before Christmas 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/dylan-thomas/pages/do-not-go-gentle.shtml|title=Dylan Thomas: Do Not Go Gentle Into That Good Night|date=6 November 2008|accessdate=18 December 2010|publisher=BBC Wales|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127042748/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/dylan-thomas/pages/do-not-go-gentle.shtml|archive-date=27 November 2012}}</ref><ref>* {{cite book|title=Fatal Neglect: Who Killed Dylan Thomas? |first=David N. |last=Thomas |publisher=Seren |year=2008|page=19|isbn=978-1-85411-480-8}}</ref> It has no title other than its first line, \"Do not go gentle into that good night\", a line that appears as a [[refrain]] throughout the poem along with its other refrain, \"Rage, rage against the dying of the light\". The poem currently remains under [[copyright]],{{refn|group=note|COPYRIGHT: from ''The Poems of Dylan Thomas'', published by [[New Directions Publishing|New Directions]]. Copyright  1952, 1953 Dylan Thomas. Copyright  1937, 1945, 1955, 1962, 1966, 1967 the Trustees for the Copyrights of Dylan Thomas. Copyright  1938, 1939, 1943, 1946, 1971 New Directions Publishing Corp.''}} although the text is available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poem/do-not-go-gentle-good-night |title=Do not go gentle into that good night &#124; Academy of American Poets |publisher=Poets.org |accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Form ==\nThe villanelle consists of five [[stanza]]s of three lines ([[tercet]]s) followed by a single stanza of four lines (a [[quatrain]]) for a total of nineteen lines.<ref name=\"Strand et al. 2001 p. 7\">Strand et al. 2001 p. 7</ref> It is structured by two repeating [[rhyme]]s and two [[refrain]]s: the first line of the first stanza serves as the last line of the second and fourth stanzas, and the third line of the first stanza serves as the last line of the third and fifth stanzas.<ref name=\"Strand et al. 2001 p. 7\"/> The rhyme-and-refrain pattern of ''Do not go gentle into that good night'' can be schematized as A<sup>1</sup>bA<sup>2</sup> abA<sup>1</sup> abA<sup>2</sup> abA<sup>1</sup> abA<sup>2</sup> abA<sup>1</sup>A<sup>2</sup> where letters (\"a\" and \"b\") indicate the two rhyme sounds, upper case indicates a refrain (\"A\"), and superscript numerals (<sup>1</sup> and <sup>2</sup>) indicate Refrain 1 and Refrain 2. See scheme below.<ref name=\"aap\">{{cite web|title=Poetic Form: Villanelle |url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5796 |work=poets.org |publisher=[[Academy of American Poets]] |access-date=23 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013133937/http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5796|archive-date=13 October 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n:Line 2 (b)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n\n:Line 4 (a)\n:Line 5 (b)\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n\n:Line 7 (a)\n:Line 8 (b)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n\n:Line 10 (a)\n:Line 11 (b)\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n\n:Line 13 (a)\n:Line 14 (b)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n\n:Line 16 (a)\n:Line 17 (b)\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Notable use in popular culture ==\n{{In popular culture|date=December 2018}}\n* \"Do not go gentle into that good night\" was used as the text for the 1954 ''In Memoriam Dylan Thomas'' (Dirge-Canons and Song) for tenor and chamber ensemble, by [[Igor Stravinsky]]. The piece was written soon after Thomas' death and first performed in 1954.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Keller | first=Hans | title=In Memoriam Dylan Thomas: Strawinsky's Schoenbergian Technique | journal=Tempo |year=1955 | issue=35 | pages=13\u201320 }}</ref>\n* It was the inspiration for three paintings by Swansea-born painter and print-maker [[Ceri Richards]], who drew them in 1954, 1956, and 1965 respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/richards-do-not-go-gentle-into-that-good-night-t00439 |title=Ceri Richards: 'Do not go gentle into that good night' 1956 |publisher=tate.org.uk/ |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\n* It is the subject of a 1979 tone poem for wind ensemble by [[Elliot del Borgo]].<ref>\"Do Not Go Gentle into That Good Night\", copyright 1979, Shawnee Press.</ref>\n*In the 1986 movie ''[[Back to School]]'', [[Sally Kellerman]] uses the poem as a test question on the final of [[Rodney Dangerfield]].\n* [[John Cale]] set the poem to orchestral music for his album ''[[Words for the Dying]]'', released in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schaeffer|first1=John|title=Five Songs For Dylan Thomas|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/five-songs-dylan-thomas/|accessdate=16 August 2017|publisher=NPR|date=27 October 2015}}</ref>\n* In the track \"Rage\" by [[Chumbawamba]] on the album ''[[Anarchy_(Chumbawamba_album)|Anarchy]]'', released in 1994.\n* The refrain \"rage against the dying of the light\" features in the song \"Down to the River\" on [[Ben Caplan]]'s 2011 album \"In the Time of the Great Remembering\".\n* In the 1995 film ''[[Dangerous Minds]]'', retired [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]] [[LouAnne Johnson]], played by [[Michelle Pfeiffer]], uses the poem to teach her students and help them identify with what they are learning in her class.\n* Electronic musician [[Richard Burmer]] released a track of the same name on his 1996 album ''Treasures of the Saints'' which features a recording of Dylan Thomas reading the poem. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/do-not-go-gentle-into-that-good-night-mt0002293502|title=Do Not Go Gentle into That Good Night - Richard Burmer &#124; Song Info|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n* In the 1996 film ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'', the President makes a rousing speech as he prepares to lead the attack against the alien invaders, adapting Thomas' line, saying, \"We will not go quietly into the night.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mair | first=Jan |journal=Futures |title=American rules, OK: Difference and otherness in 'Independence Day' |year=1998 |volume=30 |issue=10 | pages=981\u2013991 | doi=10.1016/s0016-3287(98)00100-1}}</ref>\n*The band [[Brave Saint Saturn]] includes a recording of Thomas reading his poem in their song \"Two-Twenty-Nine\" on their 2000 album ''[[So Far from Home]]''.<ref>{{youtube|l8xL9go0sHA|Two-Twenty-Nine}}</ref>{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n* The poem is referenced in the 2001 [[Digimon Adventure 02|Digimon]] anime episode \"A Million Points of Light\". After subduing the heroes and beginning to cloak the world in darkness, the villain MaloMyotismon muses, \"The dying of the light, and nothing to rage against it!\"\n* The black metal band [[Anaal Nathrakh]] has a song called \"Rage, rage against the dying of the light\" from the 2004 album ''[[Domine Non Es Dignus]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n* In a 2007 episode of ''[[Doctor Who]]'', \"[[The Shakespeare Code]]\", The [[Tenth Doctor|Doctor]], played by [[David Tennant]], quotes the third line of this poem, \"Rage, rage against the dying of the light\", to [[William Shakespeare]], played by [[Dean Lennox Kelly]]. Shakespeare says, \"I might use that.\" To which the Doctor replies, \"You can't. It's someone else's.\"\n* In [[Christopher Nolan]]'s 2014 movie ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'', the poem is used repeatedly by [[Michael Caine]]'s character Professor John Brand, as well as by several other supporting characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2014/11/05/_do_not_go_gentle_into_that_good_night_in_interstellar_back_to_school_and.html |title=\"Do not go gentle into that good night\" in Interstellar, Back to School, and many other movies: the supercut (VIDEO)|last=Wade|first=Chris|date=5 November 2014|work=Slate}}</ref> In the same movie, leading actors [[Matthew McConaughey]] and [[Anne Hathaway]] are sent into hypersleep with the final words \"Do not go gentle into that good night.\"\n* In a 2015 episode of ''[[Doctor Who]]'', \"[[The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who)|The Magician's Apprentice]]\", [[Clara Oswald]], played by [[Jenna Coleman]], quotes the first line of this poem when she discovers where the [[Twelfth Doctor|Doctor]] is and what he is up to.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3JZDF14smXfkQNdlcbsGXM5/the-magician-s-apprentice-the-fact-file|title=The Magician's Apprentice: The Fact File|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n* The poem is cited by [[G-Eazy]] in \"Intro\" on his 2015 album ''[[When It's Dark Out]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/dec/06/g-eazy-when-its-dark-out-album-review|title=G-Eazy: When It\u2019s Dark Out review \u2013 almost a crossover home run|last=Thompson|first=Ben|date=6 December 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 August 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* The band [[The World Is a Beautiful Place & I Am No Longer Afraid to Die]] released a song entitled \"Rage Against the Dying of the Light\" on their album [[Harmlessness]].\n* In 2017, Irish broadcaster ''[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]'' used the poem in a promotion for the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] qualifier second leg between [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], with [[Brendan Gleeson]] reading it as footage of famous Irish sporting moments were shown.<ref>{{youtube|_hD4kuWld7A|Denmark v Republic of Ireland preview \u2013 Rage against the dying of the light....}}</ref>\n*In the [[Parsonsfield (band)|Parsonsfield]] song \"Kick Out the Windows\", which appears on their 2018 album ''WE'', the poem is referenced in the refrain \"In the light dying, we'll rage and fight, go kickin' and screamin', into that good night.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m6bdhuCBgPQ|title=Kick Out the Windows (lyric video)|last=Parsonsfield|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n*The poem was featured as a voiceover by [[Iain Glen]] in a 2018 television advert for the [[Ford Motor Company]]. The advert was subsequently banned by the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] for encouraging driving as a way to release anger.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n*The poem is read in full by [[Iggy Pop]] as the ninth track on his 2019 album ''[[Free (Iggy Pop album)|Free]]''. He had previously recorded the poem at the request of an advertising agency, who wanted it for a commercial.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petrusich |first1=Amanda |title=The Survival of Iggy Pop |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/09/02/the-survival-of-iggy-pop |publisher=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=September 19, 2019 |date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\nThe poem is about death and how the poet thinks different types of people take it.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Bibliowiki|Do Not Go Gentle into that Good Night}}\n\n{{Dylan Thomas}}\n{{Death and mortality in art}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh literature]]\n[[Category:1951 poems]]\n[[Category:Poetry by Dylan Thomas]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in Italian magazines]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Poems about death]]\n[[Category:Quotations from literature]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in the 1950s]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|Poem by Dylan Thomas}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n\"'''Do not go gentle into that good night'''\" is a poem in the form of a [[villanelle#Form|villanelle]], and the most famous work of [[Welsh literature in English|Welsh poet]] [[Dylan Thomas]] (1914\u20131953).<ref name=poets>{{cite web|url=http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poet/dylan-thomas|title=Dylan Thomas|work=Academy of American Poets|quote=He took his family to Italy, and while in Florence, he wrote ''In Country Sleep, And Other Poems'' (Dent, 1952), which includes his most famous poem, \"Do not go gentle into that good night.\"}}</ref> Though first published in the journal ''[[Botteghe Oscure]]'' in 1951,<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferris |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Ferris (Welsh writer) |title=Dylan Thomas, A Biography |year=1989 |publisher=Paragon House |location=New York |page=283 |isbn=1-55778-215-6}}</ref> it was written in 1947 when Thomas was in [[Florence]] with his family. It was published, along with other stories previously written, as part of Thomas' ''In Country Sleep, And Other Poems'' of 1952.<ref name=poets/> The poem was also included in ''Collected Poems, 1934\u20131952'', first published by [[J. M. Dent|Dent]] in 1952.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biblio.com/collected-poems-1934-1952-by-thomas-dylan/work/13131|title=Collected Poems 1934-1952 by Thomas, Dylan|website=www.biblio.com}}</ref> \n\nIt has been suggested that the poem was written for Thomas' dying father, although he did not die until just before Christmas 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/dylan-thomas/pages/do-not-go-gentle.shtml|title=Dylan Thomas: Do Not Go Gentle Into That Good Night|date=6 November 2008|accessdate=18 December 2010|publisher=BBC Wales|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127042748/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/dylan-thomas/pages/do-not-go-gentle.shtml|archive-date=27 November 2012}}</ref><ref>* {{cite book|title=Fatal Neglect: Who Killed Dylan Thomas? |first=David N. |last=Thomas |publisher=Seren |year=2008|page=19|isbn=978-1-85411-480-8}}</ref> It has no title other than its first line, \"Do not go gentle into that good night\", a line that appears as a [[refrain]] throughout the poem along with its other refrain, \"Rage, rage against the dying of the light\". The poem currently remains under [[copyright]],{{refn|group=note|COPYRIGHT: from ''The Poems of Dylan Thomas'', published by [[New Directions Publishing|New Directions]]. Copyright  1952, 1953 Dylan Thomas. Copyright  1937, 1945, 1955, 1962, 1966, 1967 the Trustees for the Copyrights of Dylan Thomas. Copyright  1938, 1939, 1943, 1946, 1971 New Directions Publishing Corp.''}} although the text is available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poem/do-not-go-gentle-good-night |title=Do not go gentle into that good night &#124; Academy of American Poets |publisher=Poets.org |accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Form ==\nThe villanelle consists of five [[stanza]]s of three lines ([[tercet]]s) followed by a single stanza of four lines (a [[quatrain]]) for a total of nineteen lines.<ref name=\"Strand et al. 2001 p. 7\">Strand et al. 2001 p. 7</ref> It is structured by two repeating [[rhyme]]s and two [[refrain]]s: the first line of the first stanza serves as the last line of the second and fourth stanzas, and the third line of the first stanza serves as the last line of the third and fifth stanzas.<ref name=\"Strand et al. 2001 p. 7\"/> The rhyme-and-refrain pattern of ''Do not go gentle into that good night'' can be schematized as A<sup>1</sup>bA<sup>2</sup> abA<sup>1</sup> abA<sup>2</sup> abA<sup>1</sup> abA<sup>2</sup> abA<sup>1</sup>A<sup>2</sup> where letters (\"a\" and \"b\") indicate the two rhyme sounds, upper case indicates a refrain (\"A\"), and superscript numerals (<sup>1</sup> and <sup>2</sup>) indicate Refrain 1 and Refrain 2. See scheme below.<ref name=\"aap\">{{cite web|title=Poetic Form: Villanelle |url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5796 |work=poets.org |publisher=[[Academy of American Poets]] |access-date=23 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013133937/http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5796|archive-date=13 October 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n:Line 2 (b)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n\n:Line 4 (a)\n:Line 5 (b)\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n\n:Line 7 (a)\n:Line 8 (b)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n\n:Line 10 (a)\n:Line 11 (b)\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n\n:Line 13 (a)\n:Line 14 (b)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n\n:Line 16 (a)\n:Line 17 (b)\n:Refrain 1 (A<sup>1</sup>)\n:Refrain 2 (A<sup>2</sup>)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Notable use in popular culture ==\n{{In popular culture|date=December 2018}}\n* \"Do not go gentle into that good night\" was used as the text for the 1954 ''In Memoriam Dylan Thomas'' (Dirge-Canons and Song) for tenor and chamber ensemble, by [[Igor Stravinsky]]. The piece was written soon after Thomas' death and first performed in 1954.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Keller | first=Hans | title=In Memoriam Dylan Thomas: Strawinsky's Schoenbergian Technique | journal=Tempo |year=1955 | issue=35 | pages=13\u201320 }}</ref>\n* It was the inspiration for three paintings by Swansea-born painter and print-maker [[Ceri Richards]], who drew them in 1954, 1956, and 1965 respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/richards-do-not-go-gentle-into-that-good-night-t00439 |title=Ceri Richards: 'Do not go gentle into that good night' 1956 |publisher=tate.org.uk/ |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\n* It is the subject of a 1979 tone poem for wind ensemble by [[Elliot del Borgo]].<ref>\"Do Not Go Gentle into That Good Night\", copyright 1979, Shawnee Press.</ref>\n*In the 1986 movie ''[[Back to School]]'', [[Sally Kellerman]] uses the poem as a test question on the final of [[Rodney Dangerfield]].\n* [[John Cale]] set the poem to orchestral music for his album ''[[Words for the Dying]]'', released in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schaeffer|first1=John|title=Five Songs For Dylan Thomas|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/five-songs-dylan-thomas/|accessdate=16 August 2017|publisher=NPR|date=27 October 2015}}</ref>\n* In the track \"Rage\" by [[Chumbawamba]] on the album ''[[Anarchy_(Chumbawamba_album)|Anarchy]]'', released in 1994.\n* The refrain \"rage against the dying of the light\" features in the song \"Down to the River\" on [[Ben Caplan]]'s 2011 album \"In the Time of the Great Remembering\".\n* In the 1995 film ''[[Dangerous Minds]]'', retired [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]] [[LouAnne Johnson]], played by [[Michelle Pfeiffer]], uses the poem to teach her students and help them identify with what they are learning in her class.\n* Electronic musician [[Richard Burmer]] released a track of the same name on his 1996 album ''Treasures of the Saints'' which features a recording of Dylan Thomas reading the poem. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/do-not-go-gentle-into-that-good-night-mt0002293502|title=Do Not Go Gentle into That Good Night - Richard Burmer &#124; Song Info|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n* In the 1996 film ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'', the President makes a rousing speech as he prepares to lead the attack against the alien invaders, adapting Thomas' line, saying, \"We will not go quietly into the night.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mair | first=Jan |journal=Futures |title=American rules, OK: Difference and otherness in 'Independence Day' |year=1998 |volume=30 |issue=10 | pages=981\u2013991 | doi=10.1016/s0016-3287(98)00100-1}}</ref>\n*The band [[Brave Saint Saturn]] includes a recording of Thomas reading his poem in their song \"Two-Twenty-Nine\" on their 2000 album ''[[So Far from Home]]''.<ref>{{youtube|l8xL9go0sHA|Two-Twenty-Nine}}</ref>{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n* The poem is referenced in the 2001 [[Digimon Adventure 02|Digimon]] anime episode \"A Million Points of Light\". After subduing the heroes and beginning to cloak the world in darkness, the villain MaloMyotismon muses, \"The dying of the light, and nothing to rage against it!\"\n* The black metal band [[Anaal Nathrakh]] has a song called \"Rage, rage against the dying of the light\" from the 2004 album ''[[Domine Non Es Dignus]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n* In a 2007 episode of ''[[Doctor Who]]'', \"[[The Shakespeare Code]]\", The [[Tenth Doctor|Doctor]], played by [[David Tennant]], quotes the third line of this poem, \"Rage, rage against the dying of the light\", to [[William Shakespeare]], played by [[Dean Lennox Kelly]]. Shakespeare says, \"I might use that.\" To which the Doctor replies, \"You can't. It's someone else's.\"\n* In [[Christopher Nolan]]'s 2014 movie ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'', the poem is used repeatedly by [[Michael Caine]]'s character Professor John Brand, as well as by several other supporting characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2014/11/05/_do_not_go_gentle_into_that_good_night_in_interstellar_back_to_school_and.html |title=\"Do not go gentle into that good night\" in Interstellar, Back to School, and many other movies: the supercut (VIDEO)|last=Wade|first=Chris|date=5 November 2014|work=Slate}}</ref> In the same movie, leading actors [[Matthew McConaughey]] and [[Anne Hathaway]] are sent into hypersleep with the final words \"Do not go gentle into that good night.\"\n* In a 2015 episode of ''[[Doctor Who]]'', \"[[The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who)|The Magician's Apprentice]]\", [[Clara Oswald]], played by [[Jenna Coleman]], quotes the first line of this poem when she discovers where the [[Twelfth Doctor|Doctor]] is and what he is up to.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3JZDF14smXfkQNdlcbsGXM5/the-magician-s-apprentice-the-fact-file|title=The Magician's Apprentice: The Fact File|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n* The poem is cited by [[G-Eazy]] in \"Intro\" on his 2015 album ''[[When It's Dark Out]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/dec/06/g-eazy-when-its-dark-out-album-review|title=G-Eazy: When It\u2019s Dark Out review \u2013 almost a crossover home run|last=Thompson|first=Ben|date=6 December 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 August 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* The band [[The World Is a Beautiful Place & I Am No Longer Afraid to Die]] released a song entitled \"Rage Against the Dying of the Light\" on their album [[Harmlessness]].\n* In 2017, Irish broadcaster ''[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]'' used the poem in a promotion for the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] qualifier second leg between [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], with [[Brendan Gleeson]] reading it as footage of famous Irish sporting moments were shown.<ref>{{youtube|_hD4kuWld7A|Denmark v Republic of Ireland preview \u2013 Rage against the dying of the light....}}</ref>\n*In the [[Parsonsfield (band)|Parsonsfield]] song \"Kick Out the Windows\", which appears on their 2018 album ''WE'', the poem is referenced in the refrain \"In the light dying, we'll rage and fight, go kickin' and screamin', into that good night.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m6bdhuCBgPQ|title=Kick Out the Windows (lyric video)|last=Parsonsfield|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n*The poem was featured as a voiceover by [[Iain Glen]] in a 2018 television advert for the [[Ford Motor Company]]. The advert was subsequently banned by the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] for encouraging driving as a way to release anger.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n*The poem is read in full by [[Iggy Pop]] as the ninth track on his 2019 album ''[[Free (Iggy Pop album)|Free]]''. He had previously recorded the poem at the request of an advertising agency, who wanted it for a commercial.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petrusich |first1=Amanda |title=The Survival of Iggy Pop |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/09/02/the-survival-of-iggy-pop |publisher=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=September 19, 2019 |date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Bibliowiki|Do Not Go Gentle into that Good Night}}\n\n{{Dylan Thomas}}\n{{Death and mortality in art}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh literature]]\n[[Category:1951 poems]]\n[[Category:Poetry by Dylan Thomas]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in Italian magazines]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Poems about death]]\n[[Category:Quotations from literature]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in the 1950s]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:b25b:eb58:1442:606d:9507:afe7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotes)", "url_page": "//e